{"type":"tags","id":"6281"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2004"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86368"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after a high-speed motor vehicle accident with an injury to his right upper arm. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is alert and oriented with no loss of consciousness. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Secondary survey indicates no pain or concerns except for severe pain and limitation of movement in his right upper arm. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be found on further examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Loss of sensation in the anterior lateral palm and lateral three fingers","Loss of sensation on the lateral shoulder","Wrist drop and loss of sensation on the dorsal aspect of the wrist/palm","Loss of sensation to the lateral aspect of the forearm and weakness of elbow flexion","Clawing and loss of sensation of the fourth and fifth digits"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe shoulder X-ray shows an anterior dislocation of the shoulder. In an anterior dislocation of the shoulder, brachial plexus injuries are common. The most likely damaged structure is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E, which supplies sensation to a patch of skin on the inferior region of the deltoid on the shoulder, known as the regimental badge area. The axillary nerve wraps around the surgical neck of humerus, hence, is vulnerable to damage in an anterior shoulder dislocation, or a surgical neck of humerus fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of sensation in the anterior lateral palm and lateral three fingers\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate median nerve injury, which is common in carpal tunnel syndrome, and also does occur in anterior shoulder dislocation, but is less likely than an axillary nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWrist drop and loss of sensation on the dorsal aspect of the wrist/palm\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate radial nerve injury, which is common in midshaft humeral fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of sensation to the lateral aspect of the forearm and weakness of elbow flexion\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate musculocutaneous nerve injury, which is also uncommon in anterior shoulder dislocations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClawing and loss of sensation of the fourth and fifth digits\u003C/strong\u003E indicates ulnar nerve injury, which is common in a medial epicondyle fracture, and can also occur in anterior shoulder dislocations, but is less common than axillary nerve injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anterior shoulder dislocations and surgical neck of humerus fractures can cause damage to the axillary nerve","The axillary nerve provides motor supply for the deltoid and sensory supply to the lower part of the deltoid on the lateral shoulder"],"references":["Gutkowska O, Martynkiewicz J, Urban M, Gosk J. Brachial plexus injury after shoulder dislocation: a literature review. Neurosurg Rev. 2020 Apr;43(2):407-423. doi: 10.1007/s10143-018-1001-x. Epub 2018 Jun 30. PMID: 29961154; PMCID: PMC7186242."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70647"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2449"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19892"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19892"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b1fc2fd4-c786-42c7-ad7f-9a71932e1dc5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b1fc2fd4-c786-42c7-ad7f-9a71932e1dc5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":559,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70647"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-20T21:18:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-20T21:19:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2449"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86368"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"desc